[src:bobby-mathews/1871-in-baseball] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:bobby-mathews/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-mathews/1873-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1873 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-mathews/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-mathews/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-mathews/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:bobby-mathews/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:bobby-mathews/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:bobby-mathews/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:bobby-mathews/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The **1879 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1879, and saw the Providence Grays as the pennant winner of the fourth season of the National League.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League was set on expanding from a six-team league to an eight-team league.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays folded, and in its place, the league admitted the Cleveland Blues, the International Association's Buffalo Bisons and Syracuse Stars, and finally (with confirmation Milwaukee was not returning) the Troy Trojans.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] It is suggested by Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) that this season featured the first African-American to play major league baseball, William Edward White, who played one game with the Providence Grays on June 21.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] He predates brothers Moses Fleetwood Walker and Weldy Walker by five years, and Jackie Robinson by 68 years.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The 1879 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 12-games-each format that had been in place since 1877, as the National League expanded from six to eight teams, adding 24 games to each team's schedule.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Five tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings had four tie games.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Reds, Providence Grays, and Syracuse Stars had one tie game each.
[src:bobby-mathews/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at the Putnam Grounds on September 20 against the Chicago White Stockings, moving to Haymakers' Grounds for the start of the 1880 season.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] Mathews was born in 1851, in Baltimore, Maryland, and he played as a teenager with the Maryland club of that city, and he made the team a dangerous one.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] Mathews began his career at the age of 16 for the Marylands of Baltimore (a junior squad) in 1868.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] A year later, he moved to the senior club, and the following year the club declared themselves professional, resulting in the creation of the National Association of Base Ball Players (NAABP).
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] On August 19, he made his first ever start in the league against the Orientals of New York, winning 28–15.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] For the 1871 season, he and some other Maryland players signed with the Fort Wayne Kekiongas.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] On May 4, 1871, in Fort Wayne, Indiana, he pitched a shutout in the inaugural game of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA), the first professional league.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] Over his 16-year career, he had 297 wins, 248 losses, 525 complete games, with a career earned run average of 2.86.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] He had 1,528 strikeouts compared with 532 walks.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] He won 20 games 8 times, including 42 in 1874 with the New York Mutuals of the National Association, and is the only player to win 50 games or to pitch 100 games in each of three major leagues.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] Mathews umpired a few games between 1871 and 1888 and signed with the regular staff of the Players' League in 1890, returning to the AA in 1891.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] He won 20 games 8 times, including a career-high 42 in 1874 with the New York Mutuals of the National Association, and is the only player to win 50 games or to pitch 100 games in each of three major leagues.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] He is the 25th winningest pitcher in MLB history, yet has the most career innings pitched and the second-highest number of wins (behind Roger Clemens) for a pitcher not elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] He is also the pitcher with the highest number of wins without reaching 300.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] Although he was known primarily as a pitcher (doing so for 578 games), he also played games in other positions from time to time, playing 80 games in the outfield, nine as a third baseman and two as a shortstop.
[src:bobby-mathews/bobby-mathews] Mathews died in 1898 in Baltimore, at the age of 46, of paresis caused by syphilis, and is interred at New Cathedral Cemetery, also in Baltimore.
